BT 1408":"circa 1408","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1373":"1373","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","4 August 1432":"4 augustus 1432","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1335":"1335","1478":"1478","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1377":"1377","1420":"1420","about 1377":"circa 1377","about 1410":"circa 1410","1408":"1408","England":"England","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England","Henage, Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1377–4 August 1432":"about 1377–4 August 1432","1360–1390":"1360–1390","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1377–1432":"1377–1432","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1408–1478":"1408–1478","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1330–1373":"1330–1373","ABT 1408":"about 1408","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1373":"1373","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","4 August 1432":"4 August 1432","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1335":"1335","1478":"1478","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1377":"1377","1420":"1420","about 1377":"about 1377","about 1410":"about 1410","1408":"1408","England":"England","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England","Henage, Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Laughton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laughon","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Laughton  ."]},{"name":"Leighton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."]},{"name":"Lawton","meanings":["English:","habitational name, from Church Lawton in Cheshire, which is recorded as Lautune in 1086. The placename derives from Old English <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Laughton  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":5,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth de Laughton was born about 1377, in Radbourne, Derbyshire, England, her father, John de Laughton, was 43 and her mother, Allianore Chandos, was 49. She married Sir Peter de la Pole about 1410, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died on 4 August 1432, in Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"about 1377–4 August 1432":"umbes 1377–4. august 1432","1360–1390":"1360–1390","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1377–1432":"1377–1432","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1408–1478":"1408–1478","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud",